Groups - Share

1. Find the group in your preferred manner

Refer to the "Groups - Retrieve" guide to get to the groups' details.


Next, follow the indicated steps:


  • If you are getting to the group's details via the "Tools" menu in the module where the group was created (Follow step 2 in this guide)
  • If you are getting to the group's details via the "Group" module (Follow step 3 in this guide)
2. Select the group you desire by clicking once on top of it

In our case, we are checking the "Random localities in CO" group that we created earlier.

The name of the group should then become highlighted in blue.


2.1. Click the icon that has a box and a hand to access the group's properties dialog
2.2. Go to the "Security" tab in the properties dialog

Currently, the "Random localities in CO" group is only viewable by the user "lrochaprado", as it appears in the "Access" window.


2.3. Scroll the "Names" window to find users and user groups to share your group with

Let's share our locality group with the users in the "Anthropology Collections Manager" group. In the dialog, scroll until you find the group and double-click or select and click "OK" to share the group with it.


You can repeat that process as many times as you wish.


3. In the group details view, click the "Security" tab
3.1. The "Security" tab is where you can add or modify permissions

Currently, the "Random localities in CO" group is only viewable by the user "lrochaprado".


Click the "Add" button to share your group with specific users or user groups.



3.2. A dialog appears with the list of EMu users and user groups

Let's share our locality group with the users in the "Anthropology Collections Manager" group. In the dialog, scroll until you find the group and double-click or select and click "OK" to share the group with it.


You can repeat that process as many times as you wish.


3.3. Security now shows two items

And that's how you can share groups.

3.4. Note that the user group was added to the "Access" window

You can now click "OK" and you should be done.
